‚öôÔ∏è What is EC2?
Amazon EC2 lets you run virtual servers (called instances) in the cloud. These can be used for:
- Hosting websites
- Running applications or databases
- Processing big data workloads
- Practicing system administration and deployment skills

üß© Key Concepts
| Term | Meaning | 
| AMI | Amazon Machine Image ‚Äî a template with OS, software, configs | 
| Instance Type | Defines hardware capacity (e.g., CPU, RAM). Types: t2.micro, m5.large, etc. | 
| Security Group | Virtual firewall to control inbound/outbound traffic | 
| Key Pair | Used for secure SSH access to your EC2 instance | 
| Elastic IP | Static, public IPv4 address for your instance | 




[A[A[A[AüöÄ Step-by-Step: How to Launch an EC2 Instance
- Log in to AWS Console
- Go to EC2 Dashboard
- Click Launch Instance
- Choose an AMI (e.g., Ubuntu, Amazon Linux)
- Select Instance Type (e.g., t2.micro for free tier)
- Configure Instance Details (Number of instances, network settings)
- Add Storage (default is 8 GB, can be customized)
- Add Tags (like Name = MyFirstEC2)
- Configure Security Group (Allow SSH from your IP)
- Select/Create a Key Pair for login
- Launch the instance
- Use SSH to connect:
